Anonymous Sun 20 Mar 2022 16:23:18 No.46313256 Report
Quoted By:
https://desuarchive.org/trash/thread/46294658/#q46307948
>Seriously, where are the mysteries and horror stories?
Just to elab, we've had a few horror/scary stories each Halloween. If you do a deep dive into desu to see what was posted each october, you'll find a lot of things people never mention.

As for mystery, that's a really hard genre to write.
The best advice I ever got on the mystery/thiller/suspense genres was that the whodunit is the one people think of first. But all the other standard questions are options.
Why? The protag(s) know what or who, but the adventure is in tracking down the reasons. Works with all three genres and can cross with psychological horror if you're not doing suspense.
How? This is basically your "if I can't figure it out, they get away scot free" plot. Imagine a heist movie, but the protag is the head of security trying to figure out who is in on the plot. Most often seen in thrillers, not uncommon in suspense, and tends to pop up in more technical mysteries.
What? This gets overshadowed if it blends with the who question. Think of Memento, but this variation doesn't need to rely on twists like amnesia or time travel. Some mysteries become this if they reveal the who early. Like the how question, another good thriller option.
When? Really easy to do mystery with this if everyone is a suspect. I've rarely seen this used in movies, mostly because there's not enough time to set up the clues and chain off from earlier questions. It does make a damned good read if the writer knows how to hide evidence in plain sight.
Where? Like how, this is common in heist situations.

The layered approach it takes to write a good one is beyond most amateurs, and few here are going to put in the effort required to pull it off. They are in no way slow-paced and comfy stories.
There's at least two guys trying to do it now that I know of. Hopefully both complete the stories.
